            "es": "> ⚠️ **CAPÍTULO PRIORITARIO PARA TI.** Esta es la mitad de tu área débil *\"Retirement and Other Insurance Concepts\"*. Aquí perdiste puntos las dos veces. Por eso este capítulo va **más a fondo**, con los **números federales 2026 verificados con el IRS** y con un enfoque en **entender la lógica fiscal**, que es lo que el examen realmente prueba. Si dominas la pregunta madre —**¿quién pagó impuestos ya, y quién los paga al final?**— acertarás casi todo.\n\n> 🧠 **La idea que ordena TODO el capítulo:**\n> ```\n> QUALIFIED (calificado):     dinero ANTES de impuestos → se deduce hoy → TODO se grava al sacar\n> NON-QUALIFIED (no calificado): dinero DESPUÉS de impuestos → no se deduce → solo la GANANCIA se grava\n> ROTH (caso especial):       dinero DESPUÉS de impuestos → no se deduce → al sacar (calificado) NADA se grava\n> ```\n\nConceptos de este capítulo:\n\n- 8.1 **Planes calificados vs no calificados (Qualified vs Non-Qualified)**\n- 8.2 **IRA Tradicional vs Roth IRA**\n- 8.3 **Planes del empleador**: 401(k), 403(b)/TSA, pensiones (DB vs DC), profit-sharing\n- 8.4 **Planes para pequeñas empresas y autoempleados**: SEP, SIMPLE, Keogh\n- 8.5 **Reglas de distribución**: penalidad 59½, RMD (73), rollovers vs transfers, 1035\n\n> 📌 **Números federales 2026 (verificados con el IRS — se ajustan cada año por inflación):**\n> | Concepto | 2026 |\n> |---|---|\n> | Aportación IRA (tradicional o Roth) | **$7,500** + **$1,100** catch-up (50+) |\n> | Aportación 401(k)/403(b)/457 | **$24,500** + **$8,000** catch-up (50+); **$11,250** super catch-up (60–63) |\n> | Límite total plan de contribución definida / SEP | **$72,000** |\n> | Penalidad por retiro temprano | **10%** antes de **59½** |\n> | Edad de RMD (distribución mínima obligatoria) | **73** (sube a 75 en 2033) |\n\n---",
            "en": "> ⚠️ **PRIORITY CHAPTER FOR YOU.** This is half of your weak area *\"Retirement and Other Insurance Concepts.\"* You lost points here both times. That is why this chapter goes **deeper**, with the **2026 federal numbers verified against the IRS** and a focus on **understanding the tax logic**, which is what the exam actually tests. If you master the parent question — **who already paid taxes, and who pays them at the end?** — you'll get almost everything right.\n\n> 🧠 **The idea that organizes the WHOLE chapter:**\n> ```\n> QUALIFIED:      pre-tax money → deducted today → EVERYTHING is taxed on withdrawal\n> NON-QUALIFIED:  after-tax money → not deducted → only the GAIN is taxed\n> ROTH (special): after-tax money → not deducted → on (qualified) withdrawal NOTHING is taxed\n> ```\n\nConcepts in this chapter:\n\n- 8.1 **Qualified vs Non-Qualified plans**\n- 8.2 **Traditional IRA vs Roth IRA**\n- 8.3 **Employer plans**: 401(k), 403(b)/TSA, pensions (DB vs DC), profit-sharing\n- 8.4 **Plans for small businesses and the self-employed**: SEP, SIMPLE, Keogh\n- 8.5 **Distribution rules**: 59½ penalty, RMD (73), rollovers vs transfers, 1035\n\n> 📌 **2026 federal numbers (verified against the IRS — adjusted yearly for inflation):**\n> | Concept | 2026 |\n> |---|---|\n> | IRA contribution (traditional or Roth) | **\\$7,500** + **\\$1,100** catch-up (50+) |\n> | 401(k)/403(b)/457 contribution | **\\$24,500** + **\\$8,000** catch-up (50+); **\\$11,250** super catch-up (60–63) |\n> | Total defined-contribution / SEP limit | **\\$72,000** |\n> | Early-withdrawal penalty | **10%** before **59½** |\n> | RMD age (required minimum distribution) | **73** (rises to 75 in 2033) |"
