          "markdown": {
            "es": "> El **underwriting** es donde la aseguradora decide **a quién acepta, en qué categoría y a qué precio**. Es el guardián del fondo común. El examen pregunta sobre todo **de dónde saca la información** (MIB, APS, reportes) y **cómo clasifica el riesgo** (preferred, standard, substandard). La idea madre: **el underwriting existe para frenar la selección adversa** —que solo los enfermos quieran asegurarse—.\n\nConceptos de este capítulo:\n\n- 12.1 **Qué es el underwriting** y la **selección adversa (adverse selection)**\n- 12.2 **Fuentes de información** — MIB, APS, exámenes, inspection/consumer reports\n- 12.3 **Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA)** e **Investigative Consumer Reports**\n- 12.4 **Clasificación de riesgos** — preferred, standard, substandard (rated), declined\n\n---",
            "en": "> **Underwriting** is where the insurer decides **who to accept, what class to place them in, and what price to charge**. It protects the insurance pool. The exam mostly asks **where information comes from** (MIB, APS, reports) and **how risk is classified** (preferred, standard, substandard). Main idea: **underwriting exists to control adverse selection**, meaning high-risk people are more likely to seek insurance.\n\nConcepts in this chapter:\n\n- 12.1 **What underwriting is** and **adverse selection**\n- 12.2 **Information sources** — MIB, APS, exams, inspection/consumer reports\n- 12.3 **Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA)** and **Investigative Consumer Reports**\n- 12.4 **Risk classification** — preferred, standard, substandard/rated, declined\n\n---"
          }
