            "en": "| # | Term | One-line meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Risk transfer | Transfer pure risk to the insurer for a premium |\n| 2 | Pure risk | Loss or no loss only → **insurable** |\n| 3 | Speculative risk | Loss or gain → **not insurable** |\n| 4 | Peril | The **cause** of loss, such as death or fire |\n| 5 | Hazard | Something that **increases** chance or severity of loss |\n| 6 | Law of Large Numbers | More similar exposures → actual losses approach expected losses |\n| 7 | Pooling | Combine premiums to pay losses of the few |\n| 8 | Adverse selection | High risks seek insurance more than low risks |\n| 9 | Insurable interest | Genuine loss from the insured's death |\n| 10 | Insurable interest, life | Must exist **at issue**, not at death |\n| 11 | Valued contract | Pays a **fixed amount**, like life insurance |\n| 12 | Indemnity contract | Pays the **actual loss**, like property/health |\n| 13 | Mortality factor | Higher mortality → higher premium |\n| 14 | Interest factor | Higher assumed interest → lower premium |\n| 15 | Expense factor/loading | Higher expenses → higher premium |\n| 16 | Net premium | Mortality minus interest |\n| 17 | Gross premium | Net premium + expenses, what the client pays |"
